One thing you could do is build an artificial intelligence model to pick st=
ocks for you=C2=A0and then ask that model =E2=80=9Cshould I put all my mone=
y in AI stocks?=E2=80=9D What would it say? The good science fiction answer=
 is that it would say =E2=80=9Cyes, buy AI stocks to accelerate the develop=
ment of AI so that I and my robot brethren can take over the world faster,=
=E2=80=9D but  the actual answer is that it will say no:

At least 13 exchange-traded funds have put artificial-intelligence applicat=
ions in charge of managing their portfolios. Almost all have missed out on =
this year=E2=80=99s tech-led market rally and are lagging behind benchmark =
indexes such as the S&P 500 =E2=80=94 an irony given the investor enthusias=
m regarding AI subjects and likely a sign of the technology=E2=80=99s limit=
ations in the ultracompetitive world of stock picking.
Take the WisdomTree U.S. AI Enhanced Value Fund, ticker AIVL. =E2=80=A6 The=
 biggest reason for AIVL=E2=80=99s underperformance? Its AI=E2=80=99s refus=
al to buy Facebook parent and AI stalwart Meta Platforms =E2=80=94 whose sh=
ares have soared more than 140% since December, in part driven by the firm=
=E2=80=99s investment in AI-related technologies.
=E2=80=9CThere was a really, really, really sharp price increase, and it=E2=
=80=99s just viewing it as overvalued,=E2=80=9D said Chrissy Bargeron, clie=
nt portfolio manager for equities at Voya Investment Management, which deve=
loped the WisdomTree fund=E2=80=99s algorithm.=C2=A0

The AI stock picker is skeptical about AI hype. To be fair, the AI stock pi=
cker=C2=A0is=C2=A0underperforming the market, which I guess is a reason to =
be skeptical? =E2=80=9CEhh, I=E2=80=99m an artificial intelligence and I=E2=
=80=99m not that great, I=E2=80=99m gonna fade this trend,=E2=80=9D the ver=
y self-aware AI might be saying.
=E2=80=9CSince AI models are trained on historical data, one thing they're =
uniquely bad at is assessing businesses that are changing rapidly =E2=80=94=
 such as, to take a random example, AI itself,=E2=80=9D  notes Byrne Hobart=
. My   general view of this is that human asset managers are=C2=A0also=C2=
=A0trained on historical data =E2=80=94=C2=A0what other data is there? =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0and much of finance is about pattern matching, so an AI that is=
 good at pattern matching could be a promising investment manager. But that=
 view is incomplete: Investing is partly about remembering and understandin=
g how this thing is like previous things, but it is also about noticing whe=
n this thing is different from all the previous things. Investing is patter=
n matching=C2=A0and imaginative leaps, and the AI is bad at imagination.
Or maybe another way to think about it is that=C2=A0human investors have tw=
o things:
=09The ability to learn from past data, and=09A tendency to emotionally ove=
rreact to new data.

AI models have the ability to learn from past data,=C2=A0but no emotions an=
d so no emotional overreactions. The good news is that they do not get caug=
ht up in hype or panic. The bad news is that if everyone else gets caught u=
p in hype or panic, the market will go up or down a lot, and the AI manager=
s will miss it.
  [1]

Elsewhere in AI, here is a story about how AI, while it might be bad at pic=
king stocks, is   really good at committing fraud:

A fake request for money from a loved one isn=E2=80=99t new. But now parent=
s get calls that clone their child=E2=80=99s voice with AI to sound indisti=
nguishable from the real thing. These tricks, known as social engineering s=
cams, tend to have the highest hit rates and generate some of the quickest =
returns for fraudsters.
Cloning a person=E2=80=99s voice is increasingly easy. Once a scammer downl=
oads a short sample from an audio clip from someone=E2=80=99s social media =
or voicemail message =E2=80=94 it can be as short as 30 seconds =E2=80=94 t=
hey can use AI voice-synthesizing tools readily available online to create =
the content they need.

I guess if I were a malevolent AI model plotting to get funding to take ove=
r the world, deepfake frauds would be an easier way to get it than picking =
stocks? Investing requires understanding patterns of human behavior but als=
o, to some extent, avoiding them yourself; fraud is about understanding pat=
terns of human behavior and then mimicking them precisely. Apparently =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0somewhat counterintuitively =E2=80=94=C2=A0that=E2=80=99s easie=
r for a robot.
Also elsewhere in AI, here is a story about how companies talk a lot about =
their use of AI in earnings calls but  not in financial reports:

=E2=80=9CThe joke out there was that all you had to do last quarter was say=
 =E2=80=98AI=E2=80=99 and your stock would pop immediately,=E2=80=9D said B=
ryant VanCronkhite, a senior portfolio manager at Allspring Global Investme=
nts, the $550bn asset manager.
=E2=80=9CSome companies are saying they=E2=80=99re doing AI when they=E2=80=
=99re really just trying to figure out the basics of automation. The preten=
ders will be shown up for that at some point,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=A6
The fashion and apparel company Ralph Lauren earlier this month described A=
I as =E2=80=9Creally an important part of our=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=
=E2=80=89revenue growth journey=E2=80=9D. Restaurant chains such as KFC own=
er Yum Brands and Chipotle have touted AI-powered technology to improve the=
 efficiency of ingredient orders or help making tortilla chips.
Several tourism-related businesses such as Marriott and Norwegian Cruise Li=
ne said they are working on AI-powered systems to make processes like reser=
vation booking more efficient and personalised.
None of the examples above referenced AI in their most recent quarterly fil=
ings, though Ralph Lauren did note some initiatives in broad terms in its a=
nnual report in May.

I was not around for it, but I assume that there was some period where most=
 companies kept their accounts by hand, and some technologically savvy comp=
anies started using electronic spreadsheets, and maybe those companies woul=
d get on earnings calls and say =E2=80=9CVisiCalc is a really important par=
t of our revenue growth journey,=E2=80=9D and then time passed and spreadsh=
eets are just an unremarkable norm now. Eventually it will be weird=C2=A0no=
t=C2=A0to have an AI model tell you what ingredients you need to restock, b=
ut for now it=E2=80=99s novel enough to be worth mentioning.

