   =20
      =E2=80=9CSocially acceptable securities fraud=E2=80=9D
   =20
 =20

If you are the chief executive officer of a public company and you lie abou=
t the company=E2=80=99s financial or operating performance in a filing with=
 the US Securities and Exchange Commission, that is probably securities fra=
ud. But what if you lie about it in a tweet?
  [4]
 Is that securities fraud?
My basic answer, and I think the traditional answer, is that everything is =
securities fraud: If a public company, or its CEO, makes a public statement=
 about the company, and that statement is not true, then shareholders are g=
oing to sue for securities fraud. I should qualify that a little: If the=C2=
=A0stock goes up=C2=A0when the CEO makes the statement, and then it=C2=A0go=
es down=C2=A0when the statement turns out to be false, then=C2=A0that=C2=A0=
is probably securities fraud; if the market doesn=E2=80=99t react either wa=
y then it=E2=80=99s not. I just think that in 2023, there are some CEOs who=
 are pretty active on social media, who communicate material news there fir=
st, and so shareholders tend to follow them on social media and react to wh=
at they post. And if what they post is lies, then the shareholders will be =
angry, I think justifiably.
On the other hand, for many people, social media is a place to blow off ste=
am and exaggerate and communicate spontaneously and carelessly. And some CE=
Os are in both categories: They post material news about their companies on=
 social media, and they also tweet spontaneously and carelessly. They under=
stand that an earnings release needs to be carefully reviewed by lawyers an=
d accountants to make sure it is correct, but they just kind of tweet whate=
ver.
This strikes me as a genuine problem! Elon Musk is of course the main examp=
le of this: He has often announced=C2=A0material news on Twitter/X, includi=
ng the news that he was planning to buy Twitter. But he also regularly trol=
ls and makes jokes and is sarcastic and gets in hyperbolic late-night fight=
s on Twitter/X. And these things overlap:=C2=A0He has often   tweeted thing=
s about Tesla Inc. that aren=E2=80=99t true; sometimes this gets him in tro=
uble with the US Securities and Exchange Commission (because the SEC thinks=
 these tweets are material and misleading), but sometimes it doesn=E2=80=99=
t. When Musk   tweeted that a new Tesla model would fly, the SEC did=C2=A0n=
ot=C2=A0sue him for fraud, because I guess the SEC figured it was a joke. B=
ut Musk also periodically tweets that Teslas will soon be fully self-drivin=
g, and it keeps not being true, and the SEC=C2=A0has apparently=C2=A0consid=
ered taking action over=C2=A0those claims, because I guess the SEC thinks t=
hey might be misleading. There is no really bright line.
Or   last month we talked about a weird decision in a securities fraud laws=
uit against Bed Bath & Beyond Inc. and Ryan Cohen, who was for a while a bi=
g shareholder of the company. At some point Cohen tweeted a moon emoji; sho=
rtly thereafter, he dumped all his stock. Shareholders sued claiming that t=
he moon emoji was fraud, Cohen moved to dismiss the lawsuit, and a judge ru=
led against him, finding that the plaintiffs had =E2=80=9Cplausibly alleged=
 that Cohen=E2=80=99s tweet was =E2=80=A6 an expert insider=E2=80=99s direc=
tion to buy or hold.=E2=80=9D I do not think that=E2=80=99s right, though a=
 federal judge did. But I could imagine contexts in which it would be right=
, in which tweeting a moon emoji really would be securities fraud. No reall=
y bright line.
Anyway here are an  article and related  blog post by law professor Christi=
ne Hurt about =E2=80=9Csocially acceptable securities fraud=E2=80=9D:

In the 90 years since the passage of the Securities Exchange Act, the numbe=
r of ways market participants can publicly disseminate statements to invest=
ors has skyrocketed. =C2=A0Yet no regulator, legislator, or judge has answe=
red a fundamental question: Should the law distinguish between a company=E2=
=80=99s statements in a tweet and in a press release? In a new article, I p=
resent an empirical analysis of 2022 10b-5 class action lawsuits and 10b-5 =
enforcement actions by the SEC and find that social media statements are in=
creasingly the basis for fraud litigation. I argue, though, that there are =
downsides to this development and that some level of socially acceptable se=
curities fraud should be tolerated in an information society. =E2=80=A6
My article argues that 10b-5 liability could be limited to particular types=
 of public documents, as Section 11 and Section 12 liability is, or to part=
icular types of issuers. For example, nonreporting issuers should be liable=
 for their social media statements because the =E2=80=9Ctotal mix=E2=80=9D =
does not include detailed, publicly filed information. Publicly-traded issu=
ers, however, should not be similarly liable. Investors should be liable fo=
r their public statements in SEC filings, such as Schedule 13D, but not unc=
ompensated statements on investor message boards, whether emoji-filled or n=
ot.

I sympathize. I once   wrote about Musk:
The argument here is that Musk should be free to tweet anything =E2=80=9Cas=
pirational and forward-looking=E2=80=9D that pops into his head about Tesla=
, and investors should be trusted to =E2=80=9Cuse caution in evaluating=E2=
=80=9D those tweets and to give them =E2=80=9Ca strong presumption of immat=
eriality.=E2=80=9D And =E2=80=A6 shouldn=E2=80=99t they? Isn=E2=80=99t that=
 the right answer? Shouldn=E2=80=99t Musk just keep tweeting, and shouldn=
=E2=80=99t investors ignore him and get their financial data only from earn=
ings calls and press releases and securities filings? I realize that it=E2=
=80=99s not that simple: Modern markets just inevitably react to informatio=
n, and if you want to be an informed trader of Tesla stock you really don=
=E2=80=99t have much choice but to parse Musk=E2=80=99s statements for thei=
r likely truth. Still it does feel like it would be the right outcome. Reas=
onable investors, in a reasonable world, really would ignore the tweets. Or=
 they=E2=80=99d like to, anyway.
I am just not sure how it could work. You=C2=A0can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0actually =
ignore Musk=E2=80=99s tweets, or Cohen=E2=80=99s, because sometimes they co=
ntain true material information that is not yet published anywhere else. Ot=
her times, they don=E2=80=99t. The traditional solution is not to say =E2=
=80=9Cwell, if you lie about it in a tweet, that=E2=80=99s fine.=E2=80=9D T=
he traditional solution is for CEOs to be very buttoned-up and only disclos=
e material information about their companies in carefully lawyered public s=
tatements, and then blow off steam, like, in person, at the golf club, with=
 their friends.
  [5]

That solution is pretty good, but it has some flaws. One is that the modern=
 oversharing CEO probably=C2=A0is=C2=A0good for investors: If the CEO tweet=
s a lot about her company then (1) investors get more information than they=
 would in carefully lawyered filings, (2) they get it in a more convenient =
format and (3) they get it more=C2=A0clearly, without the boilerplate and h=
edging language that lawyers would add. The other is that the modern oversh=
aring CEO probably=C2=A0wants=C2=A0to be on social media all the time, prob=
ably does get some value from blowing off steam on Twitter/X, and would be =
sad to go back to only communicating in heavily lawyered securities filings=
.

