<span>[4]</span>
</a> Is that securities fraud?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My basic answer, and I think the traditional a=
nswer, is that everything is securities fraud: If a public company, or its =
CEO, makes a public statement about the company, and that statement is not =
true, then shareholders are going to sue for securities fraud. I should qua=
lify that a little: If the=C2=A0<em>stock goes up=C2=A0</em>when the CEO ma=
kes the statement, and then it=C2=A0<em>goes down=C2=A0</em>when the statem=
ent turns out to be false, then=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>is probably securit=
ies fraud; if the market doesn=E2=80=99t react either way then it=E2=80=99s=
 not. I just think that in 2023, there are some CEOs who are pretty active =
on social media, who communicate material news there first, and so sharehol=
ders tend to follow them on social media and react to what they post. And i=
f what they post is lies, then the shareholders will be angry, I think just=
ifiably.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, for many people, social med=
ia is a place to blow off steam and exaggerate and communicate spontaneousl=
y and carelessly. And some CEOs are in both categories: They post material =
news about their companies on social media, and they <em>also </em>tweet sp=
ontaneously and carelessly. They understand that an earnings release needs =
to be carefully reviewed by lawyers and accountants to make sure it is corr=
ect, but they just kind of tweet whatever.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This strikes me as a genuine problem! Elon Mus=
k is of course the main example of this: He has often announced=C2=A0materi=
al news on Twitter/X, including the news that he was planning to buy Twitte=
r. But he also regularly trolls and makes jokes and is sarcastic and gets i=
