2x1bWJpYS5lZHUvMjAyMy8wOC8xOC9zb2NpYWxseS1hY2NlcHRhYmxlLXNlY3VyaXRpZXMtZnJh=
dWQv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4220d78a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> blog post</a> by law profe=
ssor Christine Hurt about =E2=80=9Csocially acceptable securities fraud=E2=
=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the 90 years since the passage of the Secur=
ities Exchange Act, the number of ways market participants can publicly dis=
seminate statements to investors has skyrocketed. =C2=A0Yet no regulator, l=
egislator, or judge has answered a fundamental question: Should the law dis=
tinguish between a company=E2=80=99s statements in a tweet and in a press r=
elease? In a new article, I present an empirical analysis of 2022 10b-5 cla=
ss action lawsuits and 10b-5 enforcement actions by the SEC and find that s=
ocial media statements are increasingly the basis for fraud litigation. I a=
rgue, though, that there are downsides to this development and that some le=
vel of socially acceptable securities fraud should be tolerated in an infor=
mation society. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My article argues that 10b-5 liability could b=
e limited to particular types of public documents, as Section 11 and Sectio=
n 12 liability is, or to particular types of issuers. For example, nonrepor=
ting issuers should be liable for their social media statements because the=
 =E2=80=9Ctotal mix=E2=80=9D does not include detailed, publicly filed info=
rmation. Publicly-traded issuers, however, should not be similarly liable. =
Investors should be liable for their public statements in SEC filings, such=
 as Schedule 13D, but not uncompensated statements on investor message boar=
ds, whether emoji-filled or not.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I sympathize. I once <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32478013.259424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJ=
nLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDMtMTIvZG9uLXQtdGFrZS1lbG9uLW11c2stc2=
8tc2VyaW91c2x5P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA4MjIyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmd=
XRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDgyMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlz=
dHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCfdbf3586" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  wrote about Musk</a>:<=
/p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The argument here is that Musk sho=
uld be free to tweet anything =E2=80=9Caspirational and forward-looking=E2=
=80=9D that pops into his head about Tesla, and investors should be trusted=
 to =E2=80=9Cuse caution in evaluating=E2=80=9D those tweets and to give th=
em =E2=80=9Ca strong presumption of immateriality.=E2=80=9D And =E2=80=A6 s=
houldn=E2=80=99t they? Isn=E2=80=99t that the right answer? Shouldn=E2=80=
=99t Musk just keep tweeting, and shouldn=E2=80=99t investors ignore him an=
d get their financial data only from earnings calls and press releases and =
securities filings? I realize that it=E2=80=99s not that simple: Modern mar=
kets just inevitably react to information, and if you want to be an informe=
d trader of Tesla stock you really don=E2=80=99t have much choice but to pa=
rse Musk=E2=80=99s statements for their likely truth. Still it does feel li=
ke it would be the right outcome. Reasonable investors, in a reasonable wor=
ld, really would ignore the tweets. Or they=E2=80=99d like to, anyway.</p><=
/blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am just not sure how it could work. You=C2=
=A0<em>can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>actually ignore Musk=E2=80=99s tweets, or Co=
hen=E2=80=99s, because sometimes they contain true material information tha=
t is not yet published anywhere else. Other times, they don=E2=80=99t. The =
traditional solution is not to say =E2=80=9Cwell, if you lie about it in a =
tweet, that=E2=80=99s fine.=E2=80=9D The traditional solution is for CEOs t=
o be very buttoned-up and only disclose material information about their co=
mpanies in carefully lawyered public statements, and then blow off steam, l=
ike, in person, at the golf club, with their friends.<a class=3D"footnote-i=
ndex" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; dis=
play: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That solution is pretty good, but it has some =
flaws. One is that the modern oversharing CEO probably=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</e=
m>good for investors: If the CEO tweets a lot about her company then (1) in=
vestors get more information than they would in carefully lawyered filings,=
 (2) they get it in a more convenient format and (3) they get it more=C2=A0=
<em>clearly</em>, without the boilerplate and hedging language that lawyers=
 would add. The other is that the modern oversharing CEO probably=C2=A0<em>=
wants=C2=A0</em>to be on social media all the time, probably does get some =
value from blowing off steam on Twitter/X, and would be sad to go back to o=
nly communicating in heavily lawyered securities filings.</p>
